using spaces all over town

03:40.742 --> 03:42.047
to hold class.

03:42.091 --> 03:43.397
Yeah, it smells
like feet in here.

03:43.440 --> 03:44.398
Well, maybe tomorrow
you should consider

03:44.441 --> 03:45.616
wearing clean socks, Hunter.

03:45.660 --> 03:47.749
[laughter]Okay, so,

03:47.792 --> 03:50.404
despite all the changes,
we are gonna continue forward

03:50.447 --> 03:52.580
with our sophomore
study project.

03:52.623 --> 03:55.322
So you can create your
own independent project

03:55.365 --> 03:56.932
in any area you'd like.

03:56.975 --> 03:59.804
Can it be something art-related?

03:59.848 --> 04:00.979
Mm-hmm.

04:01.023 --> 04:02.633
As long as it has literary value

04:02.677 --> 04:04.592
and you submit a project
at the end of three weeks.

04:04.635 --> 04:06.028
So we can be flexible?

04:06.071 --> 04:07.595
Yes. You can be flexible.

04:07.638 --> 04:09.423
Thank you.You guys, this is your chance

04:09.466 --> 04:11.903
to create your own
curriculum, so dream big.

04:14.906 --> 04:17.605
Here's the bag
you left in the garage.

04:17.648 --> 04:19.694
You know,
I could've come and got it.

04:19.737 --> 04:21.304
I don't want you in my house.

04:21.348 --> 04:24.655
[chuckles]
Nothing changes, does it?

04:24.699 --> 04:25.961
Tell me about it.

04:26.004 --> 04:27.963
You leave Greylock
because your life

04:28.006 --> 04:29.791
is more important
than everybody else's,

04:29.834 --> 04:33.055
and then you come back
two decades later,

04:33.098 --> 04:34.970
for exactly the same reason.

04:35.013 --> 04:36.450
I came back to see my kids.

04:36.493 --> 04:37.755
Oh, really?
Did you finally get bored

04:37.799 --> 04:39.322
of running from them?

04:39.366 --> 04:41.803
I wasn't running away from them.

04:41.846 --> 04:43.413
And from what
I understand,

04:43.457 --> 04:45.937
I'm not the only one
who was running from you.

04:45.981 --> 04:49.680
Be careful. It's a long fall
from up on that high horse.

04:49.724 --> 04:50.986
I'm sure it does seem high,

04:51.029 --> 04:52.814
from down in the ditches
where you've been.

04:52.857 --> 04:55.120
Oh. Well,
from where I'm standing,

04:55.164 --> 04:59.908
I'm looking at a very selfish,
cowardly, poor excuse for a man.

04:59.951 --> 05:01.866
You just hop right back up
on that bike

05:01.910 --> 05:03.738
and take off
like it was yesterday.Last time I checked,

05:03.781 --> 05:04.913
I think you're the one
that took off.

05:04.956 --> 05:06.175
Can't imagine why.

05:06.218 --> 05:07.829
Everything bad that happened
once you were gone

05:07.872 --> 05:10.179
was because you were gone!

05:10.222 --> 05:14.270
So what you did was my fault?

05:14.314 --> 05:16.316
You're unbelievable.

05:21.712 --> 05:25.194
DANNY:
I have good news
and better news.

05:25.237 --> 05:27.283
The good news is, the first
batch of coltan is here.

05:27.327 --> 05:30.373
Tomorrow, we'll start processing
it into metallic tantalum.

05:30.417 --> 05:32.201
Less geology, more economics.

05:32.244 --> 05:34.203
That is the better news.

05:34.246 --> 05:36.684
The global price
of coltan jumped

05:36.727 --> 05:40.122
this past week thanks
to a military coup in the Congo.

05:40.165 --> 05:42.385
Well, let's make not give thanks
for a military coup?

05:42.429 --> 05:44.387
The coltan is worth more
than the market rate?

05:44.431 --> 05:46.258
We're gonna get a bump
on this first batch.

05:46.302 --> 05:48.391
How much of a bump
are we talking here?

05:48.435 --> 05:51.438
$52 million more
than we were expecting.[all gasping]

05:51.481 --> 05:53.091
And given
Sarah's deal with Lydon

05:53.135 --> 05:55.877
promises two-thirds of all
profits back to the town,

05:55.920 --> 05:57.705
which means Greylock stands
to make an extra...

05:57.748 --> 05:58.836
$35 million.

05:58.880 --> 06:00.534
What are we gonna do
with all that money?

06:00.577 --> 06:02.840
$35 million spent the
right way gets Greylock

06:02.884 --> 06:04.842
a new high school
and a new clinic.

06:04.886 --> 06:07.018
Two birds,
one super valuable stone.

06:07.062 --> 06:08.411
Hold on, the people of
Greylock, they went

06:08.455 --> 06:09.456
through a lot because
of this coltan.

06:09.499 --> 06:11.109
They deserve a
share of the spoils.

06:11.153 --> 06:12.807
This kind of money's
life-changing.

06:12.850 --> 06:15.810
Look, the population
of Greylock is what? 2,700.SARAH: 2,700.

06:15.853 --> 06:20.510
Divide $35 million by 2,700,
is about $13,000 per person.

06:20.554 --> 06:23.600
Barely enough to buy
a new car, so...

06:23.644 --> 06:25.210
to call it life-changing
is a little far-fetched.

06:25.254 --> 06:27.212
LIZ:
Whoa.For you, Mr. Manhattan address.

06:27.256 --> 06:28.953
Okay, look, hand this money out,

06:28.997 --> 06:30.215
and it's just a bunch
of raindrops.

06:30.259 --> 06:32.740
But pool it together,
and we can actually

06:32.783 --> 06:34.176
get real change in Greylock.

06:34.219 --> 06:36.308
I mean, t-those raindrops
become a flood.

06:36.352 --> 06:37.919
Wrong analogy,
considering the circumstances.Sure.

06:37.962 --> 06:39.050
Look, if we start handing out
stimulus checks,

06:39.094 --> 06:40.225
everyone's gonna spend
that money

06:40.269 --> 06:41.662
outside of Greylock.

06:41.705 --> 06:43.054
Wh-- If we hand out
stimulus checks,

06:43.098 --> 06:44.229
everyone's gonna spend
that money

06:44.273 --> 06:45.622
however they damn well please.

06:45.666 --> 06:47.145
Can we just pause for a second
and take a vote?

06:47.189 --> 06:48.712
Who wants
infrastructure?

06:48.756 --> 06:51.106
And who wants stimulus?

06:53.848 --> 06:56.894
DANNY:
Two to two.
You're the tie break, sis.

06:56.938 --> 06:58.287
Of course.

07:08.384 --> 07:10.908
[knocking on door]Hey.

07:10.952 --> 07:12.562
What're you doing here?

07:12.606 --> 07:14.477
Did Adam change his mind
about you being my friend?

07:15.522 --> 07:16.697
[clears throat]

07:16.740 --> 07:19.961
I'm not here
as your friend, Sarah.

07:20.004 --> 07:21.832
I'm here as a teacher.

07:22.964 --> 07:25.836
I know, I know, I'm sorry,
I hate it, too.

07:26.837 --> 07:29.492
Okay. Let's hear it.

07:29.536 --> 07:32.843
So, um, I know that the council
is talking about

07:32.887 --> 07:34.366
what to do with the surplus.

07:34.410 --> 07:35.672
Sarah,

07:35.716 --> 07:36.804
you have to invest it
in the school system.

07:36.847 --> 07:38.327
That option is already
on the table.

07:38.370 --> 07:40.460
I don't want it on the table.
I want it in the budget.

07:42.549 --> 07:46.248
Sarah, our school was struggling
before the flood, but now?

07:46.291 --> 07:48.163
The few resources we do have
are laughable.

07:49.207 --> 07:52.820
Rumor is, Principal Asadi is
retiring at the end of the year.

07:52.863 --> 07:54.517
I'm gonna throw my
hat into the ring.

07:54.561 --> 07:57.346
Running for the Greylock council
showed me that...

07:57.389 --> 07:58.826
maybe I can do big things.

07:58.869 --> 08:00.480
I want to put
Greylock on the map

08:00.523 --> 08:04.048
as the most progressive
school district in the world.

08:04.092 --> 08:06.094
But I can't do that
if we aren't properly funded.

08:06.137 --> 08:07.487
I know

08:07.530 --> 08:10.272
that you're still
a teacher on the inside,

08:10.315 --> 08:12.970
no matter what you
are on the outside.

08:13.014 --> 08:15.320
And teachers always put
their students first.

08:15.364 --> 08:17.018
Always.

08:19.803 --> 08:21.892
[door opens, closes]

08:21.936 --> 08:25.896
How about a dogs-only
production of A Winter's Tail?

08:27.332 --> 08:29.944
Get it? T-A-I-L?

08:29.987 --> 08:30.945
I get it.

08:30.988 --> 08:32.163
Tito can be the lead.

08:32.207 --> 08:34.296
That's-that's an A-plus
idea right there.

08:34.339 --> 08:36.951
Look, the project
needs to have literary value.

08:36.994 --> 08:38.605
I can't just dress up
a bunch of beagles

08:38.648 --> 08:40.650
in Elizabethan ruffs
and call it a day.

08:40.694 --> 08:43.131
Elizabethan ruffs?
That's-that's funny.

08:43.174 --> 08:44.436
Like, "Ruff, ruff."

08:44.480 --> 08:46.221
Ruff, ruff.

08:46.264 --> 08:47.396
Swipe left.

08:47.439 --> 08:48.615
Oh, okay.

08:48.658 --> 08:50.094
No, seriously, Ty. Thank you.

08:50.138 --> 08:51.574
Thank you for helping me out
moving into this new place.

08:51.618 --> 08:54.708
This whole thing goes
a lot faster with two people.

08:57.624 --> 08:58.929
Whoa, is this eight-millimeter?

08:58.973 --> 09:00.714
I didn't know
you were into film.

09:00.757 --> 09:03.630
Oh, that belonged to Patience.
Uh, she carried that everywhere.

09:03.673 --> 09:07.590
You could borrow
it if you like.

09:07.634 --> 09:08.852
The camera bag
has film and filters.

09:08.896 --> 09:10.593
Use whatever's in there.

09:10.637 --> 09:13.814
Are you sure? I mean, this
is your wife's special thing.

09:13.857 --> 09:15.119
I don't...No, no, I'm sure.

09:15.163 --> 09:16.860
Therapy's going well,
I'm in a better place.

09:16.904 --> 09:19.559
Camera is all, it's all yours.

09:27.436 --> 09:30.091
Well, it's official. MediCo
is buying my dad's facility.

09:30.134 --> 09:32.441
I thought it was just a rumor.[sighs] It was,

09:32.484 --> 09:35.139
but the CEO just confirmed it
in an interview.

09:35.183 --> 09:36.314
This is a nightmare.

09:36.358 --> 09:38.447
I did some digging on MediCo.

09:38.490 --> 09:40.536
Every hospital they've bought,
they've raised the cost.

09:40.580 --> 09:42.320
Okay, so move your dad
somewhere else.

09:42.364 --> 09:44.279
Places that cater to patients
like my dad,

09:44.322 --> 09:46.455
they're few and far between.

09:46.498 --> 09:48.283
Where's the next nearest one?

09:48.326 --> 09:50.807
Cape Cod.

09:50.851 --> 09:52.243
And there's no way I can
let him be six hours away.

09:52.287 --> 09:54.898
If he moves...

09:54.942 --> 09:57.335
I'd have to move with him.

09:58.467 --> 09:59.947
Well, I've been in
a good place lately.

09:59.990 --> 10:03.124
It's just... your father,
he gets to me.

10:03.167 --> 10:04.429
I know the feeling.

10:04.473 --> 10:06.214
Well, I saw him yesterday
and he brought up

10:06.257 --> 10:08.433
some of my more difficult
moments with Danny.

10:08.477 --> 10:10.174
[sighs]

10:10.218 --> 10:12.350
And as we-- as we talked...

10:12.394 --> 10:14.918
What? What'd he do?It's what he won't do.

10:14.962 --> 10:17.791
He refuses to acknowledge

10:17.834 --> 10:20.271
any damage that he has
caused this family.

10:20.315 --> 10:22.752
We've all caused
our fair share, Mom.

10:22.796 --> 10:24.493
Yes, I understand that I did
the most terrible thing.

10:24.536 --> 10:26.887
At least I'm trying
to face my faults.

10:26.930 --> 10:28.758
He is completely
ignoring the fact

10:28.802 --> 10:30.760
that when you walk
out on your family,

10:30.804 --> 10:32.370
you actually leave
them with damage.

10:34.242 --> 10:36.026
I'm really proud of the progress

10:36.070 --> 10:37.332
that you have made
in this program,

10:37.375 --> 10:38.768
but none of it
is gonna be permanent

10:38.812 --> 10:40.944
unless you can accept
that the root cause

10:40.988 --> 10:43.947
of your bad behavior
wasn't Paul,

10:43.991 --> 10:46.036
or Danny or me.

10:46.080 --> 10:48.299
There's always gonna be
someone else to blame.

10:48.343 --> 10:49.779
But if you do that,
you're never gonna confront

10:49.823 --> 10:51.302
your part
in your own failures.

10:51.346 --> 10:54.262
And if you can't acknowledge it,
you can't fix it, Mom.

10:58.353 --> 11:00.355
I know that marriage
counseling is super weird.

11:01.486 --> 11:03.227
And I know that we
have a long way to go

11:03.271 --> 11:04.968
before we feel like...

11:05.012 --> 11:07.144
us again but...

11:07.188 --> 11:09.190
this is really nice.

11:09.233 --> 11:11.061
Yeah.

11:11.105 --> 11:12.933
It was a, it was a great idea.

11:14.543 --> 11:16.371
Hey, could I get
another vodka tonic from you?

11:17.851 --> 11:19.591
Thanks.

11:19.635 --> 11:22.856
Well, I am gonna go...
powder my nose.

11:22.899 --> 11:25.206
So I can look cute
for my perfect husband.

11:31.212 --> 11:32.996
This place is great.

11:33.040 --> 11:35.042
GROVER:
Yeah. Yeah. Right?

11:35.085 --> 11:37.218
[indistinct chatter]

11:39.220 --> 11:41.483
I told you.

11:41.526 --> 11:44.181
Can I get two double
whiskeys neat?

11:47.619 --> 11:49.491
Adam. Hey, man.

11:49.534 --> 11:51.275
How you doing?

11:51.319 --> 11:53.321
Been better.

11:53.364 --> 11:56.063
Super Cooper here dropped
an A-bomb into my life.

11:56.106 --> 11:58.935
Maybe we should head
someplace else.Yeah.

11:58.979 --> 12:00.894
Yeah, yeah,
y-you would want to leave.

12:02.069 --> 12:03.897
That's Danny Cooper's
go-to move, isn't it?

12:03.940 --> 12:05.202
Oh, Adam, Adam, come on.
Okay, hey, Adam...

12:05.246 --> 12:06.987
What, am I wrong?

12:07.030 --> 12:09.859
This is the guy
who left his whole family

12:09.903 --> 12:12.644
and his girlfriend
without saying a goodbye.

12:12.688 --> 12:14.908
Then he turns around
and does the exact same thing

12:14.951 --> 12:16.823
to his fiancÃ©e.

12:16.866 --> 12:18.389
Boy, you're really

12:18.433 --> 12:21.305
batting a thousand, aren't you?Don't go there.

